ed Thrush. Because of a lack of recaptures of Swainson's Thrush in the SNSM ( n  &equals; 2), we could not test for site differences in this species.  Change in body mass between successive captures of individuals of Swainson's Thrush ( A ,  B ), Veery ( C ,  D ) and Gray-cheeked Thrush ( E ,  F ) during southward migration in the Dari&eacute;n (left) and the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta (right), Colombia. Variation in the shading of symbols reflects different years (2009&ndash;2012), and lines connect capture events of the same individual. The horizontal line is the mean lean body mass for each species. ( D ) was adapted from  Bayly et al. (2012) .  Change in body mass (expressed as percent lean body mass &lsqb;&percnt;LBM&rsqb;) in individuals of three species of thrush as a function of the number of days since first capture in the Dari&eacute;n and the Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta (SNSM). Symbols represent birds from multiple years (2009&ndash;2012), and lines represent the predicted mass-change trajectory for each species based on model-averaged parameters from models that received the greatest support from AIC values. The model with most support from AIC is shown in the table under each graph with the respective AIC, &Delta;  i  , and  w i   values. ( A ,  B ) Swainson's Thrush. ( C ,  D ) Veery, adapted from  Bayly et al. (2012) . ( E ,  F ) Gray-cheeked Thrush.  Table 5  in the Appendix shows the AIC, &Delta;  i  , and  w i   values for all the models that were evaluated.  &ldquo;Total stopover&rdquo; durations varied between 3 and 9 days for all species, with a tendency to be longer in the SNSM regardless of species ( Table 3 ). The shortest durations were those of Gray-cheeked Thrush in the Dari&eacute;n, whereas Veery in the SNSM made the longest stopovers. Models for Swainson's Thrush and Veery in the Dari&eacute;n supported the presence of transients in the population, whereas there was no evidence of transients of either species in the SNSM ( Tables 4 ,